 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=iz55>iz55</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 49<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(4/8/03 10:27 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm26.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=35.topic&index=47>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/radman.gif" align=absmiddle>  why should I get involved?</span><hr size=1> What many people do not realize, is that our government is not a monolithic phenomena, but there are many factions in constant competition for funds and influence. Entrenched bureaucracies and lifetime politicians sometimes lose sight of their service-oriented function, and see perpetuation of their &quot;fiefdoms&quot; as synonomous with their personal survival.<br>
<br>
It is the responsibility of individual people, as citizens, voters and constiuents, to insure the quality and integrity of our government. Unfortunately, Civics is not emphasized in high school, and so many are resigned that their small voice cannot make a difference that they don't participate in the democratic process. In their absence, the bureaucratics are left to act autonomously, with only the PACS and lobbyists to keep them in check.<br>
<br>
The issue of non-professional rocketry regulation is an excellent case in point. While the ATF and the various Intelligence agencies absolutely have a responsibility to the manage risks to both national security and public safety, in this case the ATF does not recognize the unworkability of their licensing proposal, nor do forsee it's cascade effects.<br>
<br>
The Safe Explosives Act has exempted schools, but makes motors &gt; 62.5g unavailable to university students at club launches because they cannot meet the storage or citizenship requrements. It is in the club environment that they get the greatest practical experience and mentoring from experienced rocketeers. It's like saying that you can go to class 3 hours a week, but homework, independent-study projects and Internships are prohibited.<br>
<br>
Then there is the detrimental impact on children who haven't gotten to the stage in their lives where they can enroll in an aerospace curriculum. The ATF will let them fly their Estes and Quest engines (assuming that the shipping exemptions all get worked out), but for the most part these children fly at launches with their parents, and the adults fly regulated motors.<br>
<br>
If the parents can't satisfy the minimum distance requirements for storage (as [sub]urbanites cannot), or they cannot obtain motors because the resellers cannot justify the cost of handling regulated products, the parents will have to abandon their level of participation. The children's opportunities to launch will be reduced significantly, if not eliminated.  (The ATF would have you believe that the &quot;contingency storage&quot; provision alleviates the storage challenge, but in practice the number and accessibility of contigency storage providers is insufficient to meet the demand.)<br>
<br>
Consequently, if the children don't fly, and get to see and be inspired by the flights of the larger adult rockets, how many will chose aerospace curriculums at all, and then where is the talent pool necessary to support our lead in space?<br>
<br>
As I said, it is the responsibility of individual citizens to help Our government stay in touch. Only then is the real potential of a democratic society realized.<br>
<br>
- iz<br>
<br>
