<br>
That is the goal we are working towards. Since its introduction, we have been working with the Judiciary committee staff. When the committee staff is satisfied with the bill, it will be brought before the members of the committee for a vote. We expect it to pass the committee. When that happens, Sen. Hatch will call the committee report on the bill to the floor of the Senate for a vote. The committee report in this case would be favorable on the bill.<br>
<br>
Assumming the bill passes the Senate vote it goes to House where it will be referred to the Judiciary committee there. Unless there is some hidden show stopper missed by the Senate Judiciary staff, it should get an ok from the House Judiciary staff. Assuming that happens, it gets voted on by the House Judiciary committee. The chairman of the House Judiciary committee calls it to the floor of the House for a vote. Assuming it passes the House, it goes to the President for a signature or veto.<br>
<br>
If the House changes the wording of the bill and then passes it, it goes to a joint Senate/House committee where the differences in the language are worked out to a common agreement. That committee then issues a report which is voted on by both the House and Senate. If the House and Senate both approve, then it goes to the President for a signature or veto.<br>
<br>
Sounds more complicated than it is. As far as time goes, the events can happen very fast depending on how it is steered through the process.<br>
<br>
The bill must be passed before Congress ends in the fall or the process must start all over again with the introduction of a new bill. So it either passes or fails before this session ends around October.<br>
<br>
John Wickman <br>
