<br>
[ this is a repost from RMR newsgroup ]<br>
<br>
In simple terms HSA is going to require all DOT regulated shippers comply with additional regulations and procedures on shipment of  &quot;explosives&quot; is 1.1, 1.2, 1.3, 1.4, 1.5, 1.6).  Keep in mind 1.3-1.6 is allowed on aircraft regularly and 1.4-1.6 is allowed on passenger aircradft.  So it is safe and stabel to ship.<br>
<br>
The reactionary regulation is not targeted at solving a parrticular problem, but a &quot;blanked response&quot; to a &quot;blanket fear&quot; of &quot;potential futire fear that has not yet actually been realized&quot;.<br>
<br>
The ATF issue is more relevent to the average rocketeer.<br>
<br>
It seeks to require an ATF explosives permit to access ANY motor with 62.6 grams or more of propellant.  The permit itself varies from $25 to $200 and only the $200 one is useful in practice.  Right after they asked rocketers yto get the one that is now $200 they raised the price of it from $50 to $200.  At the time they asked rocketeers to get the $50 permit thay sad in part, &quot;why complain, it's only $50?&quot;.  Less than 2 yers later it was $200.<br>
<br>
The permit and its fee is the smallest of the problems.  While it does force you to pay $60 for fingerprints and a background check which you submit to the Department of Justice (the nation's police force), it does not stop there.  The permit is a waiver of rights to be free from search and seizure in your place of business, residence, person or effects.<br>
<br>
But once again that is a small aspect to it.<br>
<br>
Now let's say you are one of those folks that no amount of unnecessary appeasement to the police force or state is not abhorrent to you and giving up rights is a &quot;small price to pay for public safety&quot;, no matter how safe the public was before you did that.<br>
<br>
Now you have to store these motors you have purchased with your &quot;explosives permit&quot;.  These motors (explosives) have to be stored in an approves EXPLOSIVES magazine (box).  This box has to be very specific design and security.  It has to be located in an APPROVED location.  <br>
<br>
Approved by:<br>
The ATF<br>
The state<br>
The County<br>
The city<br>
The county sheriff<br>
The city police<br>
The city or county council<br>
The local servicing fire department<br>
The county hazardous materials department<br>
Thecounty planning commission<br>
The county building commission<br>
<br>
If ANY of these folks say no or tell you to relocate it you must.  They are each entitled to charge you fees, make you fill out paperwork and draw maps, conduct interviews, make inspections, and charge fees for that, and order you to cease without notice. The permit is contingent on having this storage legally approved (merely having it physically is insufficient).  A violation is a felony, even if inadvertent.<br>
<br>
The typical offset distance for a magazine is 75 feet from any inhabited building (house, store, whatever).  To place it elsewhere you will need a &quot;variance&quot; which has to also be approved with all of the above.  To justify a variance for placing EXPLOSIVES inside a residential dwelling is difficult at best.<br>
<br>
So to get a better perspective on this consider this fact.  Your 62.0g motors can be stored anywhere including your bedroom drawer.  You can have as many as you want, say 1000 pounds.<br>
<br>
Buy a single 63.0g motor and all of the above applies.<br>
<br>
BUT buy an industrial motor from a vendor that complies with 27 CFR 55.141-a-8, you can put your 10000g motor in your bedroom drawer or closet (like the TRA President did for years).<br>
<br>
Propellant is not an explosive as defined or regulated.  Do not volunteer for explosives treatment for a non-explosive.<br>
<br>
www.v-serv.com/usr/ATFexempt.htm<br>
<br>
Jerry<br>
